u003C/span>\u003Cspan data-text=\"Ἀνίκητος\" data-n=\"25\" data-lemma=\"Ἀνίκητος\">ΑΝΙΚΗΤΟΣ\u003C/span>\u003Cspan data-text=\"ἔζησεν\" data-n=\"30\" data-lemma=\"ζάω\">ΕΖΗΣΕΝ\u003C/span>\u003Cspan data-text=\"ἔτη\" data-n=\"35\" data-lemma=\"ἔτος\">ΕΤΗ\u003C/span>\u003Cspan data-text=\"XXXX\" data-n=\"40\" data-lemma=\"XXXX\">XXXX\u003C/span>\u003C/span>\u003C/div>\u003Cp class=\"miniapp\">\u003C/p>\u003C/div>\u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"facsimile-images\">\u003Ch2>Facsimile Images\u003C/h2>\u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"apparatus\">\u003Ch4>Apparatus criticus\u003C/h4>\u003Cul>\u003Cli>\u003Cspan>  \u003Cspan>Text after Gualtherus\u003C/span>  \u003C/span>; \u003C/li>\u003Cli>\u003Cspan class=\"2\">2: \u003Cspan>Gualtherus: ΕΟΝΙΟΙΣ\u003C/span>  \u003C/span>\u003C/li>\u003C/ul>\u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"translation\">\u003Ch2>English translation\u003C/h2>\u003Cp class=\"translation-author\">\u003Ca href=\"https://orcid.org/0000-0002-0981-2465\">Matthew Hewitt\u003C/a>\u003C/p>  \u003Cp>To the gods of the Underworld. ... Soulpikios Aniketos lived 40 years.\u003C/p>  \u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"commentary\">\u003Ch2>commentary\u003C/h2>  \u003Cp>Kaibel speculates that the stone was broken at line 3, because he could not explain ΜΗΚΑΛΙ, but given that the rest of the stone is clearly intact, apart from the loss of two letters at the end of line 2, one must rather assume that some more comprehensible praenomen has been corrupted / misread. The use of Roman numerals in a Greek text is notable (and has parallels, e.g., at Catania).\u003C/p>  \u003C/div>  \u003Cdiv id=\"bibliography\">\u003Ch2>bibliography\u003C/h2>  \u003Cul>\u003Cli> Gualtherus 1624 [1625] 253 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001931\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001931\u003C/a>  \u003C/li>\u003Cli> Franz 1853 5586 \u003Ca href=\"https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001250\" target=\"_blank\">https://biblio.inscriptiones.org/epig10001250\u003C/a>  \u003C/li